<p><br /></p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Catalytic centre</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Close view of the catalytic center of the ribozyme. The A-0 O2â€² is positioned for inline nucleophilic attack (broken red line). G40 N1 is well placed to act as general base. An amino group has been modeled onto Glc6P to generate glucosamine-6-phosphate; this amine is positioned to act as general acid to protonate the G-1 O5â€² -leaving group.<br /></p>

<p>The proposed catalytic mechanism of the glmS ribozyme. In the nucleolytic cleavage reaction the 2â€²-OH of a ribose acts as the nucleophile, attacking the scissile phosphate and releasing the 5â€²-oxygen leaving group. This reaction requires an in-line (180Â°) conformation for the 2â€²-OH, scissile phosphate and 5â€²-oxygen. In the glmS ribozyme, a guanosine has been implicated in the reaction mechanism.<br /></p>
